  "prompt": "What are the types of induction motors?",
  "response": "Induction motors are commonly categorized based on their construction and starting method. Here are the primary types:\n\n1. **Single-phase induction motors**:\n   - **Split-phase induction motor**: Uses a start winding and run winding with different electrical characteristics to create a phase difference.\n   - **Capacitor start induction motor**: Uses a capacitor in series with the start winding to improve starting torque.\n   - **Capacitor start capacitor run induction motor**: Uses capacitors both in the start winding and run winding for better starting and running efficiencies.\n   - **Shaded-pole induction motor**: Uses a shaded pole for creating the necessary phase shift to start the motor; typically used in low-power applications.\n   - **Permanent split capacitor (PSC) motor**: Uses a permanent capacitor in series with the start winding that remains in the circuit during running.\n\n2. **Three-phase induction motors**:\n   - **Squirrel-cage induction motor**: The rotor is a laminated iron core with aluminum or copper bars forming a cage-like structure. This is the most common type of induction motor due to its simple and rugged construction.\n   - **Wound-rotor (or slip ring) induction motor**: The rotor has windings connected to external resistors via slip rings. This allows for control of the motor's starting characteristics and can be used for variable speed applications.\n\nEach type of induction motor has its unique advantages and applications, ranging from household appliances to industrial machinery.",
